  "prompt": "What is the difference between negative ion and electron?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between negative ions and electrons:\n\nNegative Ion:\n1. Consists of an atom or molecule that has gained one or more extra electrons\n2. Has an overall negative electrical charge\n3. Contains both electrons and protons\n4. Larger in size compared to a single electron\n5. Can exist in various forms (gas, liquid, solid)\n6. Often found in chemical compounds or solutions\n\nElectron:\n1. A fundamental subatomic particle\n2. Has a negative electrical charge\n3. Very small in size\n4. Part of an atom's structure\n5. Always carries the same amount of negative charge\n6. Can exist independently or as part of an atom\n7. Has minimal mass compared to protons and neutrons\n\nMain distinctions:\n- Negative ions are charged atoms/molecules\n- Electrons are individual subatomic particles\n- Negative ions contain multiple electrons\n- Electrons are fundamental particles with specific properties\n\nIn summary, a negative ion is a charged entity containing electrons, while an electron is a basic subatomic particle with a negative charge.",
